{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Use British English|date=September 2017}} {{Refimprove|date=April 2016}}
'''Robert Evan Kendell''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|FRSE|FRCP|FRCPsych}} (28 March 1935 − 19 December 2002) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] psychiatrist. He was [[Chief Medical Officer of Scotland]] 1991−96, President of the Royal College of Psychiatrists 1996−99.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artuk.org/discover/artworks/dr-robert-kendell-president-of-the-royal-college-of-psychiatrists-19961999-215990|title=Dr Robert Kendell, President of the Royal College of Psychiatrists (1996–1999) {{!}} Art UK Art UK {{!}} Discover Artworks Dr Robert Kendell, President of the Royal College of Psychiatrists (1996–1999)|website=artuk.org|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>
==Background== He was born on 28 March 1935 in Yorkshire, the son of teachers and spent some of his childhood in Wales.<ref name="Munk's Roll">{{cite web |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5133 |title=Munk's roll: Volume XI : Robert Evan Kendell |website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk |publisher=[[Royal College of Physicians]] |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> He was educated at the [[Mill Hill School]] in London then won a scholarship to [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]<ref>{{Who's Who | surname = KENDELL | othernames = Dr Robert Evan | id = U22837 | type = was | volume = 2018 | edition = online}} {{subscription required}}</ref>, where he was awarded a Double First in the Natural Sciences Tripos.<ref name=":0" /> After further study at the [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|King's College Hospital Medical School]] and a brief stint in internal medicine he joined the [[Maudsley Hospital]] and trained under Sir [[Aubrey Lewis]].<ref name="Munk's Roll"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pb.rcpsych.org/content/pbrcpsych/18/1/2.full.pdf|title=INTERVIEW: R.E. Kendell|last=Kerr|first=Alan|date=1994|website=Psychiatric Bulletin|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Kendell was later awarded the [[Gaskell Medal]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1417352/Dr-Robert-Kendell.html|title=Dr Robert Kendell|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>
Aged 38 he was appointed to the chair of psychiatry in [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]]. In 1986 he was made the Dean of the Medical School and during his four years in this post he supervised a period of expansion.<ref name="BMJ obituary">{{cite journal |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1125141/pdf/286.pdf |pmc=1125141 |title=Robert Evan Kendell |journal=[[BMJ]] |volume=326 |date=1 February 2003 |pages=286|doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7383.286}}</ref> In 1991 he was appointed the Chief Medical Officer of Scotland. In 1997 he was elected the president of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]] and served for a three-year term. As Chief Medical Officer, he worked to build awareness of the influence of diet and smoking on health, as well as contributing to the responses to [[Bovine spongiform encephalopathy]] and [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref name=":0" />
==Research== He published more that 200 papers during his career, continuing after he had retired from employment.<ref name="BMJ obituary"/> Much of his work focussed on the classification and diagnosis of mental disorders<ref name=":0" />
==Awards and honours== He was made a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in 2002.<ref name="Guardian obituary">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jan/18/guardianobituaries.obituaries |title=Robert Kendell |first=Ian |last=Bouchier |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 January 2003 |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> He was elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (FRSE). He was awarded the Paul Hoch Medal of the [[American Psychopathological Association]]; and the [[Marne Medal|Marce Medal]]. He was a member of the World Health Organisation's Expert Advisory Panel on Mental Health for 12 years.<ref name=":0" />
==Death== On 19 December 2002 he collapsed and died later that day, of an unsuspected brain tumour.<ref name="BMJ obituary"/>
