{{Malay name|Taufik|Zahar|note=on}}

The '''shooting of Taufik Zahar''' took place around 4.36&nbsp;am on 31 May 2015, near the [[Shangri-La Hotel Singapore|Shangri-La Hotel]] in [[Singapore]] where the [[Shangri-La Dialogue]] was being held; police officers fatally shot Mohamed Taufik bin Zahar, a 34-year-old logistics mover.<ref name="planning-new-life">{{cite news |last= Cheong|first=Danson |date=4 June 2015 |title=Shangri-La Shooting: Wife of man shot by police says they were planning new life together |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-wife-of-man-shot-by-police-says-they-were-planning-new-life-together |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |accessdate=30 December 2015 }}</ref> Taufik, who was driving a red [[Subaru Impreza]] and was carrying two passengers, had encountered a [[roadblock]] set up in relation to the dialogue. When instructed to open the Subaru's [[Trunk (car)|boot]] for checks, Taufik accelerated the vehicle towards police officers, crashing through concrete barriers erected by the police, and continued driving the vehicle despite repeated warnings to stop. Anticipating threats to their safety, police officers [[handgun|opened fire]] at the vehicle and shot Taufik dead through the windscreen.<ref name="spf-statement">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1 June 2015 |title= Consolidated Update to Incident along Orange Grove Road  |url=http://www.police.gov.sg/mic/2015/06/20150601_others_incident_orange_grove_consolidate_update.html |location=Singapore |agency=Public Affairs Department, Singapore Police Force |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229175057/http://www.police.gov.sg/mic/2015/06/20150601_others_incident_orange_grove_consolidate_update.html |archivedate=29 December 2015 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>

After the incident, the two passengers, Mohamed bin Ismail and Muhammad Syahid Mohamed Yasin, were convicted of [[Drug-related crime|drug offences]] and sentenced to 8 and 7 years' [[prison|jail]] respectively, and 3 strokes of [[Caning in Singapore|the cane]] each.<ref name="ismail-conviction">{{cite news |last=  Malinda|first= Kyle |date= 15 June 2015|title=Shangri-La shooting: Man sentenced to jail, caning for drug offences |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-man/1916190.html |newspaper=Channel NewsAsia |location= Singapore|accessdate= 30 December 2015}}</ref><ref name="syahid-conviction">{{cite news |last=Chelvan |first=Vanessa |date=21 December 2015 |title=Shangri-La shooting: Man who encouraged friend to crash through police barrier jailed, caned |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-man/2224884.html |newspaper=Channel NewsAsia |location=Singapore |accessdate=30 December 2015 }}</ref>

This is the fourth police shooting in Singapore in 15 years.<ref name="rare">{{cite news |last=Goy |first=Priscilla |date=1 June 2015 |title=Shangri-La shooting: Police shootings very rare in Singapore |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-police-shootings-very-rare-in-singapore |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore|accessdate=30 December 2015 }}</ref> Taufik's wife, Nassida Nasir, opined that death was disproportionate punishment for Taufik,<ref name="stomp-nassida-nasir">{{cite news|date= 2 June 2015|title=Wife of man shot dead at Police checkpoint blames SPF -- claiming that hubby was only driving without licence |url=http://singaporeseen.stomp.com.sg/this-urban-jungle/wife-of-man-shot-dead-at-police-checkpoint-blames-spf-claming-that-hubby-was-only |newspaper=Stomp |location=Singapore |accessdate= 30 December 2015}}</ref> but the public was generally supportive of the actions of the police.<ref name="public-opinion">{{cite web |url=http://publicopinion.sg/358/shangri-shooting-most-support-some-question-police-action |title= Shangri-la shooting - Most support but some question police action |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |date=2 June 2015 |website=Public Opinion |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref> The Singapore government has also defended and commended the actions of the police officers.<ref name="st-teo-chee-hean">{{cite news |last=Mohamad Salleh |first=Nur Asyiqin  |date=14 July 2015 |title=Shangri-La shooting: Police 'acted in line with procedure' |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/shangri-la-shooting-police-acted-in-line-with-procedure |newspaper=The Straits Times |location= Singapore|accessdate=30 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name="mha-teo-chee-hean">{{cite press release |last=Teo |first=Chee Hean |date=13 July 2015 |title=
Oral Reply to Parliamentary Question on Orange Grove Road Incident by Mr Teo Chee Hean, Deputy Prime Minister, Coordinating Minister for National Security and Minister for Home Affairs
 |url=https://www.mha.gov.sg/Newsroom/in-parliament/oral-replies-to-pqs/Pages/Oral-Reply-to-Parliamentary-Question-on-Orange-Grove-Road-Incident-by-Mr-Teo-Chee-Hean,-Deputy-Prime-Minister,-Coordinating.aspx |location=Singapore |agency=Ministry of Home Affairs |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229180553/https://www.mha.gov.sg/Newsroom/in-parliament/oral-replies-to-pqs/Pages/Oral-Reply-to-Parliamentary-Question-on-Orange-Grove-Road-Incident-by-Mr-Teo-Chee-Hean,-Deputy-Prime-Minister,-Coordinating.aspx |archivedate=29 December 2015  |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> A coroner's inquiry into the death of Taufik is scheduled.<ref name="st-teo-chee-hean" /><ref name="mha-teo-chee-hean" />

